WEBVTT

00:01:02.462 --> 00:01:04.164
...say bye-bye...

00:01:04.164 --> 00:01:05.698
Narrator:
Children's experiences

00:01:05.698 --> 00:01:07.400
during their first five years

00:01:07.400 --> 00:01:10.870
are more consequential
than we ever thought.

00:01:10.870 --> 00:01:12.872
Woman:
We know that the brain

00:01:12.872 --> 00:01:16.509
develops the most
in the first five years of

00:01:16.509 --> 00:01:21.181
By age 6, 95% of a child's brain
is already developed.

00:01:21.181 --> 00:01:22.515
By age 6!

00:01:22.515 --> 00:01:25.678
So these early years
are very very important.

00:01:26.686 --> 00:01:28.321
Narrator:
And of all people,

00:01:28.321 --> 00:01:29.255
not just parents,

00:01:29.255 --> 00:01:31.324
pediatricians and teachers,

00:01:31.324 --> 00:01:34.225
but economists
are paying attention.

00:01:36.596 --> 00:01:38.331
Man:
Neural synaptic connections

00:01:38.331 --> 00:01:40.333
are occurring in a child's brain

00:01:40.333 --> 00:01:43.770
age zero to three
at a rate of 700 a second.

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:45.405
The worst fallacy in
this business

00:01:45.405 --> 00:01:48.842
is to assume that the abilities,
the motivations,

00:01:48.842 --> 00:01:51.845
the skills of people are fixed
at birth - they are not.

00:01:51.845 --> 00:01:52.779
Dugger:
What happens in that

00:01:52.779 --> 00:01:55.348
36-month period is important

00:01:55.348 --> 00:01:58.218
as far as whether a child
is going to be trusting

00:01:58.218 --> 00:02:00.353
and curious, and active

00:02:00.353 --> 00:02:01.955
and able to interact with

00:02:01.955 --> 00:02:04.082
other people in a
productive way.

00:02:04.791 --> 00:02:06.126
Heckman:
What I came to understand

00:02:06.126 --> 00:02:08.628
was that ability
was multiple in nature,

00:02:08.628 --> 00:02:11.531
that you could actually start,
even at the earliest years,

00:02:11.531 --> 00:02:13.266
and increase the possibilities

00:02:13.266 --> 00:02:16.102
of individuals for their life.

00:02:16.102 --> 00:02:17.804
So that became
very exciting to me.

00:02:17.804 --> 00:02:20.039
(children screaming
in excitement)

00:02:20.039 --> 00:02:21.564
It's moving!
You woke it up!

00:02:23.610 --> 00:02:24.611
Man:
Here I am,

00:02:24.611 --> 00:02:26.813
at the Federal Reserve Bank
of Minneapolis,

00:02:26.813 --> 00:02:30.216
my expertise is
pre-Civil War banking,

00:02:30.216 --> 00:02:32.886
I worried a lot about
business cycles

00:02:32.886 --> 00:02:34.420
and financial crises,

00:02:34.420 --> 00:02:35.752
and unemployment
and inflation.

00:02:36.990 --> 00:02:40.293
How does somebody
with that background

00:02:40.293 --> 00:02:42.495
get involved with
early childhood,

00:02:42.495 --> 00:02:43.622
prenatal to five?

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.804
You have to figure out
what's the best investment?

00:02:51.804 --> 00:02:54.107
It's going to be early
childhood education.

00:02:54.107 --> 00:02:55.768
Making sure these kids
start healthy

00:02:55.842 --> 00:02:56.707
and ready to learn.

00:02:57.677 --> 00:02:58.978
Narrator:
Science has demonstrated

00:02:58.978 --> 00:03:02.081
that a child's earliest
experiences are vital

00:03:02.081 --> 00:03:06.186
to building the foundation
for life-long individual success

00:03:06.186 --> 00:03:08.288
in school and in life.

00:03:08.288 --> 00:03:11.121
We can put dollar values
on almost anything...

00:03:11.824 --> 00:03:13.760
Narrator:
Economists are adding new data

00:03:13.760 --> 00:03:15.328
to this argument,

00:03:15.328 --> 00:03:17.964
studying two initiatives
in particular:

00:03:17.964 --> 00:03:22.435
high-quality early care
and preschool,

00:03:22.435 --> 00:03:24.704
calculating how much they cost,

00:03:24.704 --> 00:03:28.072
and how much they pay off
to our economy.

00:03:29.209 --> 00:03:31.110
And they're worried.

00:03:31.110 --> 00:03:33.513
Not because we're spending
too much,

00:03:33.513 --> 00:03:36.182
but because we're spending
too little

00:03:36.182 --> 00:03:37.673
where it matters most.

00:03:39.452 --> 00:03:40.820
Rolnick:
You can make moral arguments

00:03:40.820 --> 00:03:43.389
for Higher Ed, for K-12,

00:03:43.389 --> 00:03:46.326
for reducing crime,
for reducing pollution.

00:03:46.326 --> 00:03:49.062
But policy makers need more
than moral arguments.

00:03:49.062 --> 00:03:51.064
We asked
a very direct question

00:03:51.064 --> 00:03:54.033
that most economists
or business people would ask:

00:03:54.033 --> 00:03:55.933
"What was the return
on the investment?"

00:03:58.304 --> 00:03:59.706
Narrator:
The first study to catch

00:03:59.706 --> 00:04:02.208
the attention of Rolnick and
other economists

00:04:02.208 --> 00:04:05.078
was from a high quality
early childhood experiment

00:04:05.078 --> 00:04:08.414
for low-income children
in Ypsilanti, Michigan,

00:04:08.414 --> 00:04:09.882
called Perry Preschool.

00:04:12.986 --> 00:04:15.421
Founded in 1962,

00:04:15.421 --> 00:04:18.891
Perry Preschool grew out
of the spirit of that time-

00:04:18.891 --> 00:04:20.994
the growth of the
civil rights movement,

00:04:20.994 --> 00:04:23.656
desegregation
and equal opportunity.

00:04:24.731 --> 00:04:27.367
The Perry children
had master's level teachers

00:04:27.367 --> 00:04:30.336
and low
student-to-teacher ratios.

00:04:30.336 --> 00:04:34.374
Educators even visited the
families at home every week.

00:04:34.374 --> 00:04:36.175
Polk:
The children that were receiving

00:04:36.175 --> 00:04:40.613
the Perry intervention
received three hours per day

00:04:40.613 --> 00:04:43.750
of a cognitively rich
preschool program.

00:04:43.750 --> 00:04:46.452
They focus on things
such as math,

00:04:46.452 --> 00:04:49.222
literacy, play-based
approaches,

00:04:49.222 --> 00:04:52.458
focus on engaging
their imagination

00:04:52.458 --> 00:04:54.188
and their own investment
in their learning.

00:04:57.797 --> 00:04:58.898
Narrator:
The Perry kids

00:04:58.898 --> 00:05:01.234
were compared to
a group of their peers,

00:05:01.234 --> 00:05:05.138
a control group,
who weren't in the program.

00:05:05.138 --> 00:05:09.742
Both groups have been
followed for 40 years.

00:05:09.742 --> 00:05:11.044
Rolnick:
They found that the children

00:05:11.044 --> 00:05:14.147
that were in
the high-quality program

00:05:14.147 --> 00:05:18.418
were less likely to be retained
in the first grade,

00:05:18.418 --> 00:05:22.322
were less likely
to need special ed,

00:05:22.322 --> 00:05:25.158
were more likely to be literate
by the sixth grade,

00:05:25.158 --> 00:05:30.496
graduate high school, get a job,
pay taxes, start a family.

00:05:30.496 --> 00:05:33.599
And the crime rate
between the two groups,

00:05:33.599 --> 00:05:35.935
the randomized group
and the control group,

00:05:35.935 --> 00:05:38.063
the crime rate
goes down 50%.

00:05:39.739 --> 00:05:41.607
So those looked like
pretty good outcomes!

00:05:41.607 --> 00:05:45.945
They became what we think of as
model citizens in our country,

00:05:45.945 --> 00:05:47.879
despite their modest beginnings.

00:05:50.016 --> 00:05:51.317
Narrator:
And those outcomes

00:05:51.317 --> 00:05:53.920
equal hard dollars.

00:05:53.920 --> 00:05:55.855
The program was expensive.

00:05:55.855 --> 00:05:59.692
But economists calculated
the benefits:

00:05:59.692 --> 00:06:01.361
the Perry students
were more likely

00:06:01.361 --> 00:06:03.096
to stay on track in school,

00:06:03.096 --> 00:06:07.300
have higher skilled jobs
and contribute more in taxes,

00:06:07.300 --> 00:06:09.836
and less likely
to incur the social costs

00:06:09.836 --> 00:06:12.638
of welfare and prison.

00:06:12.638 --> 00:06:14.140
Polk:
The youngest children

00:06:14.140 --> 00:06:16.809
of the Perry Preschool studies
are now 52

00:06:16.809 --> 00:06:19.112
and the oldest children of the
Perry Preschool studies

00:06:19.112 --> 00:06:20.680
are now 56.

00:06:20.680 --> 00:06:22.315
So we've been following children

00:06:22.315 --> 00:06:25.718
from the Perry Preschool
experiment for 50 years.

00:06:25.718 --> 00:06:28.621
What did we learn?
Many things.

00:06:28.621 --> 00:06:30.123
It's very successful

00:06:30.123 --> 00:06:32.692
in terms of the economic
performance of the children.

00:06:32.692 --> 00:06:34.627
For each dollar invested,

00:06:34.627 --> 00:06:38.531
you get back somewhere between
7% and 10% per annum

00:06:38.531 --> 00:06:40.400
over the lifetime of the child.

00:06:40.400 --> 00:06:42.095
Which is a huge rate of return.

00:06:43.669 --> 00:06:44.670
Narrator:
That translates,

00:06:44.670 --> 00:06:49.142
depending on the study,
to a payoff of $7 to $16

00:06:49.142 --> 00:06:53.346
for every dollar spent
on the program.

00:06:53.346 --> 00:06:54.347
Heckman:
What we found is

00:06:54.347 --> 00:06:55.515
some of those same traits

00:06:55.515 --> 00:06:58.251
that are starting to
be fostered early in life -

00:06:58.251 --> 00:07:01.421
solving problems but also
getting along with others

00:07:01.421 --> 00:07:04.023
and basically planning
in a wise way-

00:07:04.023 --> 00:07:07.857
pay off,
and pay off substantially.

00:07:10.530 --> 00:07:12.165
Narrator:
Yet, despite the benefits,

00:07:12.165 --> 00:07:14.667
today, public investment
in affordable,

00:07:14.667 --> 00:07:16.569
high-quality programs
like Perry

00:07:16.569 --> 00:07:21.507
is so low, only a fraction of
our children can attend them.

00:07:22.909 --> 00:07:26.512
But up north,
just across the U.S. border,

00:07:26.512 --> 00:07:28.714
one place took note
of the lessons

00:07:28.714 --> 00:07:30.376
offered by the Perry model.

00:07:38.624 --> 00:07:39.926
Twenty years ago,

00:07:39.926 --> 00:07:44.297
Quebec was the poorest
province in Canada.

00:07:44.297 --> 00:07:46.299
It was stuck in a recession,

00:07:46.299 --> 00:07:49.496
and one-quarter of its citizens
lived in poverty.

00:07:50.903 --> 00:07:52.438
The Prime Minister was alarmed

00:07:52.438 --> 00:07:55.374
by skyrocketing
social welfare costs.

00:07:57.109 --> 00:07:59.445
He asked psychologist
Camil Bouchard

00:07:59.445 --> 00:08:02.540
to head a task force
to come up with solutions.

00:08:04.250 --> 00:08:06.586
Bouchard and his
friend Lyse Brunet,

00:08:06.586 --> 00:08:08.821
a feminist and
political activist,

00:08:08.821 --> 00:08:12.621
became allies in a growing
political movement.

00:08:30.243 --> 00:08:32.078
Brunet:
In those days in Quebec,

00:08:32.078 --> 00:08:34.347
there was a lot of marches
in the street,

00:08:34.347 --> 00:08:36.449
and it was a context, I think,

00:08:36.449 --> 00:08:40.353
where the women's movement
was very strong,

00:08:40.353 --> 00:08:42.822
and it was really the women

00:08:42.822 --> 00:08:45.882
who put forward
the daycare issues.

00:08:48.194 --> 00:08:49.629
Narrator:
Nine years later,

00:08:49.629 --> 00:08:53.199
investments in high quality
early childcare programs

00:08:53.199 --> 00:08:55.535
became central
to Bouchard's strategy

00:08:55.535 --> 00:08:58.871
for reining in Quebec's
rising social costs.

00:08:58.871 --> 00:09:01.807
His team was inspired -
ironically enough -

00:09:01.807 --> 00:09:05.845
by research coming out
of the United States.

00:09:05.845 --> 00:09:08.214
Bouchard found
the evidence compelling.

00:09:08.214 --> 00:09:10.616
And not just Perry Preschool,

00:09:10.616 --> 00:09:12.285
but also Abecedarian,

00:09:12.285 --> 00:09:15.154
an intensive
experiment like Perry,

00:09:15.154 --> 00:09:19.625
this one in North Carolina,
which ran for five years.

00:09:19.625 --> 00:09:21.861
It provided infant and
toddler care,

00:09:21.861 --> 00:09:23.963
as well as preschool.

00:09:23.963 --> 00:09:25.698
One gain?

00:09:25.698 --> 00:09:27.166
Kids from the program

00:09:27.166 --> 00:09:30.836
were four times as likely
to graduate from college.

00:09:30.836 --> 00:09:33.072
The kids in the treatment group
were no smarter.

00:09:33.072 --> 00:09:36.809
But you could measure
their performance in class,

00:09:36.809 --> 00:09:39.178
and later ratings of how
successful they are

00:09:39.178 --> 00:09:40.846
in controlling their anger,

00:09:40.846 --> 00:09:42.481
dealing with
their fellow students,

00:09:42.481 --> 00:09:45.384
negotiating with each other.

00:09:45.384 --> 00:09:47.186
Narrator:
Economists calculated all

00:09:47.186 --> 00:09:50.323
the costs and benefits
30 years later.

00:09:50.323 --> 00:09:52.858
The net return to society?

00:09:52.858 --> 00:09:57.023
Nearly $100,000 for every child.

00:09:58.864 --> 00:10:02.535
The Canadians also studied
the Child Parent Center,

00:10:02.535 --> 00:10:04.570
a special half-day pilot program

00:10:04.570 --> 00:10:08.908
for low-income preschool
children in Chicago.

00:10:08.908 --> 00:10:12.578
The net return to society
in reduced social costs alone

00:10:12.578 --> 00:10:18.618
from the Chicago program was
more than $84,000 per child.

00:10:18.618 --> 00:10:20.386
Bouchard:
It was pretty clear that

00:10:20.386 --> 00:10:24.056
in applying that type
of social programs

00:10:24.056 --> 00:10:26.425
we would have success

00:10:26.425 --> 00:10:29.462
in diminishing the vulnerability
of our children.

00:10:29.462 --> 00:10:32.829
It was inspiring also because
the methodology was beautiful.

00:10:33.432 --> 00:10:35.067
Narrator:
Bouchard and his team

00:10:35.067 --> 00:10:38.437
looked to the U.S. research
and asked themselves:

00:10:38.437 --> 00:10:40.306
Could investing in
young children

00:10:40.306 --> 00:10:43.674
and their families improve
personal outcomes

00:10:43.743 --> 00:10:46.507
and reap economic
benefits in Quebec?

00:10:47.780 --> 00:10:49.715
They were convinced it could,

00:10:49.715 --> 00:10:53.419
and released a report
with 53 recommendations.

00:10:53.419 --> 00:10:55.321
Bouchard:
But the main thrust of it was

00:10:55.321 --> 00:10:59.458
that we were to approach
the problems

00:10:59.458 --> 00:11:02.587
well before they manifest
themselves, well before.

00:11:03.496 --> 00:11:06.999
We had decided that
the government should invest

00:11:06.999 --> 00:11:08.763
in the period from 0 to 5.

00:11:10.136 --> 00:11:11.470
If you had to choose,

00:11:11.470 --> 00:11:13.871
this is where you had
to start with.

00:11:14.507 --> 00:11:15.975
Narrator:
When Bouchard and his team

00:11:15.975 --> 00:11:18.678
released the report in 1992,

00:11:18.678 --> 00:11:20.846
the public reaction
was ecstatic.

00:11:20.846 --> 00:11:22.648
Bouchard:
The title of the report

00:11:22.648 --> 00:11:24.617
was kind of smashing-

00:11:24.617 --> 00:11:27.712
"We're Crazy About Our Kids,"
Quebec Fou de Ses Enfants.

00:11:29.355 --> 00:11:31.590
I was just astonished
at how many reporters,

00:11:31.590 --> 00:11:33.592
from all over the place
was at the press conference,

00:11:33.592 --> 00:11:36.429
for a governmental report.

00:11:36.429 --> 00:11:38.531
And there was something special,

00:11:38.531 --> 00:11:40.658
there was a buzz
around the title.

00:11:41.667 --> 00:11:42.868
Narrator:
Advocates for children

00:11:42.868 --> 00:11:44.670
were galvanized.

00:11:44.670 --> 00:11:46.272
Bouchard:
We met with very, very,

00:11:46.272 --> 00:11:48.174
very involved people

00:11:48.174 --> 00:11:50.342
and interested people
in the community.

00:11:50.342 --> 00:11:53.212
They had read the report,
they were ready to do something.

00:11:53.212 --> 00:11:56.148
And there was an enormous
pressure on the government

00:11:56.148 --> 00:11:58.583
to create something significant.

00:12:14.667 --> 00:12:16.736
If you just put the report
on the table

00:12:16.736 --> 00:12:17.670
and then say to government:

00:12:17.670 --> 00:12:20.906
"You should do that," and go
to fishing or hunting

00:12:20.906 --> 00:12:23.209
or to do something else,
it won't happen.

00:12:23.209 --> 00:12:27.646
You have to have a constituency
around the report.

00:12:27.646 --> 00:12:31.917
It was, like, little projects
for a couple of months

00:12:31.917 --> 00:12:36.388
and after that, they wouldn't
have any money to continue.

00:12:36.388 --> 00:12:40.493
So it was step-by-step
asking the government

00:12:40.493 --> 00:12:43.462
to put in place a real
strong system.

00:12:45.431 --> 00:12:47.600
Narrator:
By 1997, advocates

00:12:47.600 --> 00:12:49.068
had broad support,

00:12:49.068 --> 00:12:51.771
and the government
started a childcare system

00:12:51.771 --> 00:12:54.899
intended for any family
in Quebec.

00:12:55.541 --> 00:12:58.567
The tuition: five dollars a day.

00:13:01.447 --> 00:13:03.883
It would cost almost a
billion dollars

00:13:03.883 --> 00:13:05.451
in the first year alone,

00:13:05.451 --> 00:13:07.920
and no one knew if it
would actually

00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:10.082
reduce poverty and social costs.

00:13:11.223 --> 00:13:13.592
Woman:
Investing in early childhood

00:13:13.592 --> 00:13:15.928
is a no-brainer at this point.

00:13:15.928 --> 00:13:17.930
But when you start
a network like that,

00:13:17.930 --> 00:13:22.935
knowing not only the initial
investment to get it going

00:13:22.935 --> 00:13:25.871
and really the structural change
that you're putting in place,

00:13:25.871 --> 00:13:31.877
and the annual recurring cost,
there are a lot of risks.

00:13:31.877 --> 00:13:34.113
(speaks French)

00:13:34.113 --> 00:13:35.948
Narrator:
Any Robillard directs

00:13:35.948 --> 00:13:39.418
a child development center,
known as a CPE,

00:13:39.418 --> 00:13:41.216
in the Montreal neighborhood
of Villeray.

00:13:43.055 --> 00:13:48.289
Today, sixteen years later,
parents pay seven dollars a day.

00:14:19.258 --> 00:14:20.960
Narrator:
Most every afternoon

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:24.530
Alexi Chartrand,
a freelance media producer,

00:14:24.530 --> 00:14:26.464
picks up his son Vladimir.

00:14:40.546 --> 00:14:42.948
Narrator:
CPE spots are coveted-

00:14:42.948 --> 00:14:45.384
there still aren't enough
to go around.

00:14:45.384 --> 00:14:49.388
Vladimir was on a waiting list
for two years.

00:14:49.388 --> 00:14:50.723
Alexi:
It's actually,

00:14:50.723 --> 00:14:53.292
it's like a call from God.

00:14:53.292 --> 00:14:57.529
I have tons of friends that
are on the list and waited.

00:14:57.529 --> 00:14:59.331
When they called us...
at first we didn't believe it,

00:14:59.331 --> 00:15:00.900
because normally most
of my friends

00:15:00.900 --> 00:15:02.568
called before they
have their child

00:15:02.568 --> 00:15:04.832
so, "Oh, you're pregnant!
All right, let's call."

00:15:08.374 --> 00:15:10.476
Narrator:
Alexi's wife Veronique works

00:15:10.476 --> 00:15:12.311
part-time in the evenings,

00:15:12.311 --> 00:15:14.473
and by day pursues
her education.

00:15:16.215 --> 00:15:18.384
The CPE system has
turned out to be

00:15:18.384 --> 00:15:22.588
a good investment for Vladimir,
but also for his family.

00:15:22.588 --> 00:15:24.890
Veronique's schooling will
boost her family's

00:15:24.890 --> 00:15:27.382
life-long income
and well-being.

00:15:28.327 --> 00:15:32.331
If Vladimir had not gotten
a spot at a CPE,

00:15:32.331 --> 00:15:34.663
none of this would
have been possible.

00:15:37.102 --> 00:15:38.737
Narrator:
Quebec's childcare system

00:15:38.737 --> 00:15:41.273
is costly, and most
of the returns

00:15:41.273 --> 00:15:43.833
will pay out when
children grow up.

